&#xa0;
[normal]Written Evidence from the Association of Police and Crime Commissioners [CST0016][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Association of Police and Crime Commissioners (APCC) is the
[normal] national body which supports 
[normal]Police and Crime Commissioners (‘
[normal]PCCs
[normal]’)
[normal] and other local policing bodies
[normal].  This document sets out the key views that have been expresse
[normal]d by 
[normal]PCCs 
[normal]and their officers
[normal].  S
[normal]ix
[normal] PCC offices responded
[normal] 
[normal]through us
[normal] 
[normal]to the questions set out by the I
[normal]nquiry 
[normal](although it is possible that others responded direct
[normal] without copying us in)
[normal].  The following overview summarises the key comments and issues they raised
[normal], and their individual responses are 
[normal]set out in the 
[normal]Annex [bold]submitted with this document.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Background[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Public Administration
[normal] Select
[normal] Commit
[normal]t
[normal]ee 
[normal](PASC) 
[normal]will no doubt be aware of some of the key background material to this Inquiry, including the Home Office proposals and consultation on crime outcome, the UK Statistics Authority consultation on aligning the Code of Practice, and recent HMIC Inspection repo
[normal]rts on police crime recording – the most recent 
[normal]‘The Crime Scene’ dating to January 2012.   This latter report in particular has guided some of the answers set out below in relation to the understanding of the accuracy of crime data.  We believe that HMIC 
[normal]will shortly start a Data Quality inspection, which will look again at crime recording data in forces and may provide some interesting insights into some of the questions posed by the Inquiry.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Consistency and comparability
[normal] 
[normal]has emerged as a key common is
[normal]sue raised by the PCCs that responded.  
[normal]This is a complex area and there are anomalies caused in part by the system and in part by the nature of statistics.  In the case of the former, for instance, Anti-Social Behaviour incidents 
[normal]do not count as crimes un
[normal]der the rules, and the lin
[normal]e between ASB, public disorder and low level violence is often blurred
[normal].  There is also some local flexibility in how rules are applied
[normal] (for instance the time during which a crime must be recorded), which can also cause some anomal
[normal]ies.   There are a number of caveats that apply to statistics and raw data no matter how accurate it is, such as the need to 
[normal]interpret and triangulat
[normal]e 
[normal]with other evidence, before 
[normal]i
[normal]t can be coherently understood.
[normal]  These issues are explored in more detail be
[normal]low in the context of the questions set out by the PASC.  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Specific Points[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1
[normal]              
[normal]Are crimes being recorded by the police when they should be? Are crimes being categorised correctly?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The general feeling which PCCs expressed
[normal], based on internal and external 
[normal]checks, was that
[normal] crimes were being recorded and categorised correctly
[normal] on the whole
[normal], within the
[normal]ir areas and within the
[normal] limitations imposed by the system
[normal] and the nature of statistics themselves.
[normal]  However, human error and a number of the other issues addresse
[normal]d at Q2 do lead to discrepancies, but as
[normal] noted 
[normal]at Q3
[normal], there are a number of checks and balances incorporated in the system already to try to ensure that recording and categorisation is accurate
[normal], although the nature of checks and balances can vary.  Taken t
[normal]ogether this means 
[normal]that there are some inconsistencies nationally and some dangers inherent in direct comparisons of raw data.
[normal]   
[normal]Some PCCs are also concerned that b
[normal]udget cuts might impact on resources dedicated to quality control
[normal], and some PCCs feel that t
[normal]he whole system is too process based and does not taken enough account of victims’ views and needs, or allow for a common-sense approach
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2
[normal]              
[normal]What are the factors which can influence police mis-recording of crime?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A number of factors have been suggested by PCCs.  One of the key issues identified is the short time slot allowed under the rules for officers to record an incident as a crime, which puts pressure on them 
[normal]to make a judgement, 
[normal]without sufficient time to con
[normal]sider all the circumstances, and especially the victim’s wishes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Other factors suggested include human error,
[normal] subjective interpretation, complexity of HO Counting Rules and
[normal] lack of knowledge (particularly in relation to rarer types of crime
[normal], or recording 
[normal]of multiple crimes arising from one incident
[normal]),
[normal] 
[normal]the bureaucracy of the process itself (which can result in short cuts being taken)
[normal], organisational culture (particularly around compliance issues, such as reluctance to challenge fellow officers), and level of
[normal] scrutiny.  Several respondents also noted th
[normal]at targets can encourage perverse incentives, but also noted that the trend generally both from Government and PCCs is to move away from targets which has helped the problem of ‘gaming’ to meet ‘quotas’.  But th
[normal]ere is still some feeling that the general pressure to show reduced rates of crime might still be leading to 
[normal]some down-grading of crime incidents to non-crime incidents, such as ASB. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3
[normal]              
[normal]Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for 
[normal]recording crime function effectively and accurately?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are a significant number of quality control checks already in place, although the nature and depth of scrutiny can vary from force to force.  However, typically as a minimum, these would include i
[normal]nternal audit, crime registrar, external checks, such as periodic HMIC inspection, 
[normal]triangulation with other data, 
[normal]and a degree of oversight from force management board and PCC. 
[normal]  
[normal]Much depends on the quality of the audit, although s
[normal]ome forces 
[normal]also 
[normal]include a
[normal]dditional checks, such as external audit, dip sampling of crime recording and categorisation examples, additional levels of internal control process, or
[normal] 
[normal]IT systems which 
[normal]flag
[normal] erroneous data.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Greater transparency can also play a role in raising standards
[normal] and 
[normal]highlighting areas of concern – although it should be noted that there remain concerns about the extent to which data is truly comparable, for reasons already noted, and whether comparison of this nature is desirable, given the more local focus of PCC
[normal]s.  Ultimately, it is for PCCs to hold the force to account (through the Chief Constable), and they will be concerned to ensure that crime recording meets local needs and expectations (see Q6 below).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4
[normal]              
[normal]Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of cri
[normal]me data? What more should be done?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is a balanc
[normal]e to be struck between accuracy
[normal] and the cost of quality control mechanisms
[normal], and some PCCs raised concerns about whether existing checks are sustainable in the current financial climate.  
[normal]The anticipated 
[normal]HMIC Data Quality Inspection should throw some interesting light on 
[normal]what more could be done
[normal], and some PCC respondees suggested 
[normal]that new mobile technology may help, or perhaps more training
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, a 
[normal]more fundamental debate may be
[normal] needed 
[normal]a
[normal]bout whether di
[normal]screpancies from place to place are 
[normal]an inevitable consequence of greater local accountability
[normal] and responsiveness to victims (
[normal]provided the differences 
[normal]this generates 
[normal]are transparent
[normal], understood
[normal] and accounted for
[normal])
[normal], or whether 
[normal]consistency and comparability ar
[normal]e paramount, 
[normal]which would involve 
[normal]greater ce
[normal]ntralisation
[normal], s
[normal]tricter rules
[normal] and probably higher costs flowing from the greater bureaucracy involved.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5
[normal]              
[normal]To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crim
[normal]e by police forces?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Most PCCs 
[normal]who 
[normal]responded felt that some confidence could be place
[normal]d
[normal] in the data
[normal] (given its limitations)
[normal], 
[normal]and that it was a key factor in how they held the
[normal]ir
[normal] force to account.  They acknowledge there are problems with comparability (for r
[normal]easons already discussed), but at least some PCCs felt that the key issues was whether it met the needs of local communities, not necessarily national policy makers.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There was some feeling that the 
[normal]real question here was whether the public had confidence in the data, and whether something should be done to improve their perception of statistics.  
[normal]There was also some concern that there is anecdotal evidence that some crimes, including serious crimes a
[normal]re not reported by the public and some thought is needed as to how communities can be encouraged to fully report crime.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6
[normal]              
[normal]Should recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There were mixed feeling on this amongst the PCCs that 
[normal]responded.  Some thought they should as it would help with perceptions of independence, one thought this could only really work for long term trends, but others thought this should be substantially a local issue and the
[normal]refore not a National Statistic.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Annex[bold]&#xa0;[bold]TO APCC Submission to PASC Inquiry into Crime Statistics[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Individual Responses from PCCs[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]A.[bold]              [bold]Devon and Cornwall[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Please find below our responses to the questions posed by the above inquiry.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The fundamental dilemma highlighted here is the focus on accuracy rather than reliability. In answer to the questions posed (i.e. is the data accurate?) the response would be that most forces endeavour to meet the National Crime Recording Standards and the
[normal] Home Office Counting Rules and adhere to high standards of ethical recording practices. However the more pertinent question seems to be whether data can be compared between forces with confidence (i.e. is the data reliable). The answer to this is almost c
[normal]ertainly not. There is a degree of flexibility in the system currently that whilst recording in accordance with the guidance set out in the National Crime Recording Standards and within agreed time frames there are significant differences in how the result
[normal]ing data is interpreted. For example with regard to when a crime is recorded, in Devon and Cornwall we direct record (as soon as an offence is disclosed it is recorded on the crime system and is not necessarily recorded first on the incident management sys
[normal]tem). This means that if we subsequently discover that no offence was committed we have to provide evidence that no offence took place before we can no-crime. In terms of comparison to other forces this means that not only do we have a higher no-crime rate
[normal] than might otherwise be expected but also that more offences remain on the record than might be the case for other forces who conduct some early investigation to corroborate the occurrence of an offence. In addition how each force interprets the NCRS can 
[normal]vary slightly but significantly, for example the line between anti-social behaviour (a non-crime incident), public disorder (an offence against society) and low level violence (a victim-based crime) is very blurred. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Politics – an issue or offence that is high on the national or local political agenda may influence the tendency of either individuals or organisations to record an offence in a certain way. This is not to suggest that 
[normal]figures are deliberately manipulated but rather that there is a human tendency to want to conform. 
[normal]Scrutiny – whether local performance frameworks or HMIC inspections, scrutiny can influence compliance. In addition to the potential for perverse incentives
[normal] through performance frameworks there is also potential for forces to adopt recording practices that are not necessarily compatible with other forces following an adverse inspection.
[normal]Human error – whether systematic as a result of competence or the result 
[normal]of a distraction or an off-day the police crime recording system is heavily reliant on people, their abilities, attention and attitudes, and as such is vulnerable to associated limitations.
[normal]Organisational culture – an organisation that promotes integrity, 
[normal]personal responsibility and has a sound supervision structure in place is likely to achieve a high level of compliance and to identify non-compliance issues earlier.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime function
[normal] effectively and accurately? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Current checks include internal force audits, external inspections, publication of data, the Crime Survey for England &amp; Wales and crime comparator systems. The Police &amp; Crime Commissioners have a role to play in monitoring t
[normal]rends and holding forces to account where the information emerging from existing checks indicates an issue relating to recording. What seems to be missing is any means of identifying and accounting for the intrinsic differences in how forces record offence
[normal]s.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Interestingly the questions posed do not address explicitly the recording of outcomes against offences, which potentially raises further issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A balanced app
[normal]roach is needed to ensure that the data is as accurate and reliable as possible, and that limitations in the data are openly recognised and as far as possible accounted for without compromising operational delivery or imposing a significant financial burde
[normal]n. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are a number of potential solutions to the issues raised. Perhaps the most extreme would be to consider centralising crime recording such that forces record and manage incidents from the incident log but a national or regional team would determ
[normal]ine whether the incident was a crime and record this appropriately. An even more robust recording framework, mandating the point of crime recording and outcomes might offer some solution however it runs the risk of becoming operationally unwieldy and unwor
[normal]kable. A further alternative is to accept that there will always be difference and instead to identify a means of measuring more reliably, and accounting for, variability in compliance between forces.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To what extent can policy-makers have confidence i
[normal]n the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forces?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This question speaks more to how the data is used and interpreted than to either the accuracy or the reliability of the data. Police recorded data in isolation is often not the 
[normal]best data source and even police forces will use other available data sources including other partners and proxy data to identify and address policy issues. The confidence of policy-makers needs to be in the capability and competence of analysts to use the
[normal] data appropriately, to recognise its limitations and to address these through other valid sources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Should recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It isn’t entirely clear what this would deliver to address the issues raised. 
[normal]If this would add weight to forces to improve compliance or support a more robust recording framework then there might be some value.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B.[bold]              [bold]Dorset[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Committee is interested in receiving responses to the following questions: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In my view yes to the first question. The NCRS has become more and more proscriptive, and Force Registrars and HMIC regularly audit the crimes. There is a gap between ASB reports and
[normal] recording, but as these are not technically crimes, I think the Forces in general comply well. I know Dorset has, I scrutinise this closely, and HMIC have praised the Force in 2011. However, the cuts are reducing governance and oversight staff, so this co
[normal]uld get worse.
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The second question is the same, once the call enters the system, various balances and checks exist to ensure categorisation is appropriate. One thing that does need sorting is the “72 hour rule” that most Forces adopt to serious sexual offe
[normal]nce allegations. Research shows that what is reported at 3am on a Saturday night as a rape is often downgraded in the cold light of day, hence Forces adopting the 72 hour rule. I think this should be stopped, BUT it will lead to a massive increase in rape 
[normal]allegations that, when scrutinised later, are actually indecent assaults. 
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of knowledge of the hundreds of crime categories, and failure to embrace more than one offence. For exam
[normal]ple, an ex partner harassing a partner could be DA and harassment, but only one or the other would be recorded. Likewise with trafficking of humans, often the different offence in relation to CSE, forced labour or prostitution is recorded, not embracing th
[normal]e bigger picture. I have dealt with a case where a constituent had her foot run over by an offender in a parking dispute. The police recorded this as an RTA, when it was in fact an assault. And RTA v Assault brings lots of issues for the victim, especially
[normal] in relation to disclosure and compensation. 
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of time, and lack of correct oversight, as the cuts bite, Crime Registrar staff and CMU supervisors are being cut
[normal]Yes, please see above
[normal]I am happy the checks and 
[normal]balances are in place, but we cannot be complacent.
[normal]Pretty well, except for the overriding issue of – What happens if crime isn’t 
[normal]being recorded. I remain convinced that lack of faith in police action and lack of faith in the 101 service leads a massive amount of crime being unreported.
[normal]Yes they should.
