[normal]2.[bold]              [bold]W[bold]hat are the factors which can influence police mis-recording of crime?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.[bold]              [bold]Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime function effectively and accurately?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]              
[normal]Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.
[normal]              
[normal]To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police Forces?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.
[normal]              
[normal]Should record[bold]ed crime statistics be classified as National Statistics?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]E.[bold]              [bold]Surrey[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our comments on the questions posed on crime statistics: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Generally police are recording crime when reported.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The main area of current concern we have is over cybercrime.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Fraud cybercrime has 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]been taken out of police crime statistics, leading to an impression of crime going down.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] But we know thi
[normal]s is a large growing area of criminality often going un-reported.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We need to ensure that Action Fraud data is included in crime statistics in the future. 
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Setting targets on specific crime types can influence mis-recording – potentially lea
[normal]ding to mis-categorisation of crimes e.g. recording burglary as criminal damage in order to meet crime reduction or detection targets.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Generally the move by many PCCs away from targets should lead to more ethical behaviour and better integrity in crime r
[normal]ecording. 
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Forces all have force registrars and internal audit processes, but little is currently done on ensuring that there is consistency across forces in how they interpret Home Office counting rules and record data.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] However, data is co
[normal]mpared in national reports so there should be consistency. 
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] We need to balance bureaucracy involved in audits and checking with the benefit given by confidence in data.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] In recent years there has been a lack of audit and checking but hopeful
[normal] that the forthcoming HMIC inspection into crime data integrity will provide information on data quality
[normal].[bold]&#xa0;[bold] [bold]5.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Crime data provides one data set that can be used with some confidence by policy makers, bearing in mind the comments about on lack of
[normal] quality assurance on consistency.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] But crime data should be put into
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]context with other information such as the crime survey of England and Wales, changes in Home Office counting rules which affect the data and other demands on policing when making policy
[normal] decisions. 
