[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]F.[bold]              [bold]Thames Valley[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]As PCC for Thames Valley, I am reasonably assured that the Force (TVP) is recording crime in an appropriate and ethical manner.  The evidence for this is founded on two key sources. Firs
[normal]tly, HMICs thematic review (late 2011) of TVPs crime and data quality.  This showed that the Force had the best 
[normal]accuracy rates for crime recording. Additionally, TVP was the only force in the country with 100% accuracy in relation to ‘No Crime’ decisions. 
[normal]HMI concluded that ....
[normal]‘The force has high standards when recording crimes and incidents in a consistent and accurate manner to correctly reflect the sequence of events as described by victims’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Secondly, an Internal Audit of TVP’s Performance Management 
[normal]function was carried out in April 2013. The key controls for the collection and recording data were given full and/ or majority assurance.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Pressures to reduce crime rates could act as perverse incentives for some crimes to be downgraded, or, downgrading ASB related incidents (which are not captured in data returns to the Home Office). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The move to Neighborhood Policing may have also led to m
[normal]ore low level crimes being dealt with informally and outside the formal crime recording system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]  Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime function effectively and accurately? [bold]&#xa0;[bold]As mentioned above, both HMIC and our 
[normal]own OPCC Internal Audit Section undertake periodic reviews of the Force’s performance systems – this assurance informs our confidence of TVP’s crime recording systems.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, it would be short-sighted not to recognise some of the wider issues affecting 
[normal]crime recording systems. Anecdotal evidence across wider policing circles suggests that league tables and performance targets have created a culture of ‘Gaming’ – manipulating crime data to meet targets and measures.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]External checks need to better focus o
[normal]n Police culture, particularly around high ethical standards to ensure practices are conducted in a consistent manner. Other key areas are the skills and training of staff, backed up with sound quality assurance processes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Earlier this year, the Kent PCC commissioned HMIC to examine Kent Police’s crime and resolution figures to ensure that local people had confidence in the accuracy of such figures. Findings from this i
[normal]nspection found that the force had under recorded crime, and, that crime was not being resolved in accordance with national requirements.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There need to be further examples in which HMIC ‘name and shame’ Chief Constables/Forces where similar sharp practice
[normal]s may be happening elsewhere. Failure to tackle this issue may, at best, suggest not enough expertise within HMIC to shine a light on such practices; at worse, highlight a more cynical complicity in this type of culture.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]To what extent can policy-make[bold]rs have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forces?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Policy makers do have confidence in the statistics – they are able to triangulate quantitative and qualitative sources of data/information to create an informed picture. Statistics in isolation can be 
[normal]misleading and can be used incorrectly. Great care need
[normal]s to be used when quoting statistics to ensure the context is properly explained. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Perhaps the key question here is not whether policy-makers have confidence in the statistics, but ‘
[normal]do the public believe the statistics they are being told? (Difference bet
[normal]ween the perception of crime and the actual crime).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.[bold]&#xa0;[bold] Should recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics? [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Yes, classifying crime statistics as National Statistics would go some way to demonstrate better independence and more effecti
[normal]ve governance and accountability (as displayed by the Home Office who transferred this function over to the ONS). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, given all government departments are operating in a climate of challenging austerity measures, there is a counter-argument which questions what the true cost-benefits of ‘National Statistics’ are. Who benefits the most: policy makers and statistic
[normal]ians, or the public? Are the public interested - how can they be better engaged in such matters?   If you were a victim of crime, what would matter the most to you? 
[normal]&#xa0;
